snippet.textDisplay:
I rarely write comments on YouTube but this video was too interesting not to.
It hurt me really bad to watch the discussion about inequality because it is just so so so wrong that everybody can make it. A lot of them only think about how they made it and how perhaps a lot of people in privileged countries can make it but they do not think once about those people living in "third world countries" that you visit to "see poverty".

I have had the honor to meet some of the kindest, smartest, hard-working women in El Alto, Bolivia, that did not have the tiniest chance to ever become anywhere near rich. They were born into an extremely poor family, they always have some kind of disease because the food they eat is bad due to being cheap, the water they drink is polluted, they perhaps do not even have a near access to water, they have no medicin and no doctors near them.
Also they do not have the money to buy contraceptives, so they often have many children and to care for many children you need a lot of time and also some money. Everytime they earn some money, they directly have to invest it in things like food, water or health care to make sure their family is okay.
There is not one opportunity for them to get rich and that describes inequality. One of the biggest problems or even the biggest issue humankind has to deal with it. It makes me very sad that some people in this video do not realise that.

Also in some countries for some countries the internet still is a privilege. And having the time and freedom to learn from the internet how the stock market works is another privilege.

This video made me really angry because it depicts so clearly why there is so much inequality in our society.

snippet.textDisplay:
Anyone who says they're more than 20% "self-made" are ignorant, at best.
How can someone be self-made in a system where a "self-made" person makes 0.05% of the total effort. Engineers have built the infrastructure for you. Workers manufacture you depend on, and they often do it for a few dollars a day.
No one is "self-made": they're lucky. Lucky to be in the situation where they can leverage the hard work of others.
Did any of these people mine the metal ores? Engineer the required equipment? Farm the food required to feed the suckers who mine the ores for a few dollars? Work the oil-fields for the fuels required to transport the ores? Fiddle with the components until assembly? Research the years of science required to engineer-and-reengineer the technological marvels we have?
Did you fight for your own laws, by writing the legislation that gives you the proper environment to thrive? And then enforce these same laws? Did you transform your own sewage so you don't drown in it, and thus are free to pursue less meaningful pursuits for society?

No.
All you do is start a camera that an entire ecosystem has provided you with, and you present yourself in clothes manufactured by the sweat of others.

No one is self-made, except the delusional or ignorant ones that don't understand how much was already done for them before they even remotely got started.

snippet.textDisplay: Timothy attacking Christianna for her response to the first statement was pretty revealing. You can passionately disagree with someone and still respect their experience. Sure, he seems to have a naturally over-expressive personality, but his attack seems to come from a place of privilege denial. If you acknowledge that you started in life with one or many advantages, including financial/economic ones, how can you later argue that hard work alone helped you reach the heights you did? Yet he does exactly this, so he can uphold this longstanding idea that poor people choose to be poor.
